headline: Former French Prime Minister Gabriel Attal pushes ahead with presidential bid, despite doubts within party
subhead: Criticized internally for his political positioning and strategy, the former French prime minister rejects comparisons with his longtime mentor, Emmanuel Macron.

headline: Pressure on Trump intensifies after ICE kills a second US citizen
Russia steps up attacks on Ukraine's shipping routes in the Black Sea
Why the Israeli army doubts Hamas can be demilitarized
subhead: The second phase of Donald Trump's 'peace plan' for Gaza calls for the disarmament of the Islamist group. However, Israeli security leaders are convinced that it will continue to maneuver in order to maintain its capacity for both military and terrorist action.

headline: 'The MAGA movement is divided in the face of Trump's openly imperial ambitions'
subhead: A significant segment of Donald Trump's supporters is in favor of isolationism. However, most of them would continue to follow the American president as long as he retains the backing of evangelical conservatives, political scientist Thomas Charrayre writes.

headline: François Kollar shines a light on Parisian workers between the World Wars
subhead: A former lathe operator at Renault, François Kollar became one of the leading photographers of the industrial world in interwar France. Between 1931 and 1934, he traveled across the country to photograph workers on the job. Several photographs from this series, taken in Paris, have been selected by the Musée Carnavalet for an exhibition dedicated to the capital city's residents.

headline: Valeria Bruni Tedeschi: 'With the rise of the far right, artists feel crushed'
subhead: In an interview with Le Monde, the actress, who plays the legendary Italian stage performer Eleonora Duse in Pietro Marcello's latest film, discusses the difficult situation facing film d'auteur in Italy.

France is considering banning phones in high schools. This school near Paris already does.
subhead: The Lycée Michelet, a large school complex with 2,300 students, banned mobile phones in its hallways in April 2025. School officials report positive results from a decision made in agreement with the entire educational community.

headline: Falling birth rate in France: 'We may be witnessing a period of very rapid and highly gendered social change'
subhead: The decline in the number of births should be seen in connection with the 'gender divergence' between increasingly progressive young women and increasingly conservative young men, observes economist Pauline Grosjean in her column.

headline: How surveillance companies track smartphone users through advertising data
subhead: Companies are offering law enforcement agencies the ability to track smartphone users through advertising data gathered on their devices. Le Monde attended confidential presentations of these new surveillance tools to learn more.
